spanGrp.span: lēn qōn̄ ne vōwal kaka din 'a kelgi lusuwēn so lēn 'a lēn mērig

In the second half of this, the speaker stumbles and restarts a couple of times. He refers to the place where the story is situated, which is the village of Lemerig. This village lies in the other side of a coastal point and the area can be reached only by canoe. It is commonly referrd to by Vera'a speakers as 'the other side', in downwind direction from Vera'a village.
One day - this story is from the other side over there, from Lēmērig.
The clausal core consists only of the predicative NP, and this type of non-verbal clause expresses existence of the NP's referent.
One day there were the people of Lemerig.
vaga dir ga van qel dir ga vovon̄odo lēn me' ne vōwal rōvrōv'en vonore
All the time they went down [to the sea] and went fishing and collecting shells at one reef close to their home [village].
When they went fishing and collecting shells,
dirēk mul kal dirēk bigbig ēn gorēn vovon̄odo sin mes dirēm da sin goto sin wōkalkal sin wōsēs senē

"bigbig" denotes the non-staple component of a usually two-component meal. It translates as "mit" into Bislama (Engl. 'meat') and can be meat, fish, other seafood, vegetables like cabbage or cucumber. Bigbig is usually cooked in coconut cream.
then they went up home and ate their catch: fish which they prepared, hermit crab, crab or shells; like this.
dirēk mul 'ō kal lēn vonore dirēk big
They took it up to their village and had it [with sth. else].
dirēm da senē vagam da vaga da vaga vavan
They did it like this all the time, did it all the time
lēn qōn̄ ne vōwal e ruwa vōruō duru mak leg 'i
when one day there was a couple, the two had just got married,
The clause is not considered for GRAID glossing as it is a mere repetition of the previous clause (cf. Bickel 2003; Haig & Schnell 2011)
yes, the two had just got married.
durum 'ēqel rek lēn me' duruk vovon̄odo
The two went down to the reef to go fishing.
lēn masōgi durum vovon̄odo qē' duruk mul kal den
When the two finished fishing and collecting shells the two left and went up home.
'an̄sara ne vōwal wuva dim kalak den ēn m̄ogi gēr lēn 'ēnēs qōn̄ gēr senē
One person only, he came out of his house, probably in the middle of the night, like this.
di ne 'ēqel lēn me' rek di ne sin̄ ēn mugin nev lēn lēn m̄ogi
He went down to the reef, too; he lit a light in his house
and also went down to the reef.
dim 'ēqel 'an me' dim sōsōk kelkel 'an me' 'anē van van van
When he went down to the reef, he started to look around on the reef until
dim m̄alrow den so n me' dim kalaka
he was shocked for the reef, it got up.
'enei di ne qē'ēg van sir ēn 'ekē ga rōr
Now it began to move towards a deep spot / towards the dep sea.
ba di masōgi dim 'ēn sier so me' dim da 'esenē dim m̄alrow den di ne rara
And he, when he noticed that the reef it was doing thishe was shocked and cried.
di ga moros rōw lēn naw ba di mas da m̄as
He wanted to jump into the sea, but he couldn't do so
managi si dim rōw lēn naw di me 'ul
because if he jumped into the sea, he would drown.
So he just let it do so,
and so he was standing on the reef now.
lēn masōgi di ne n me' ne vanvan rak lik row lēn 'ekē ga rōr di ne sōk sier son me' dim gis reksen dim van ma reksen 'an̄sara
While it ... the reef was moving further out (into the sea) towards where it is deep, he found that the reef, it became like a person / human being.
dim rērē kal reksen 'aval n̄ēn̄ērē' me' dim rērē kal den ēn naw di ne tek mē diē so bul
It craned its neck upwards like one end of the reef it stretched out of the sea and said to him: "Friend,
nik van man lēn kolok lēn basbas nagi itok gēduk van tetel

Constructional error with the common article inserted after the directional particle 'hither'. A locative PP expressing the goal of the movement follows rather than an object NP -- which would not be licensed by the valency of the VC here anyway.
come onto my back, onto the end of it, then, all right, we two go."
so nik m 'enei gēduō va'a lēn venē lama
"You ... now we are in the middle of the sea."
itok so gēduk 'ēqel lēn vunuō ne vōwal dir ga ul son Torres lēn suwēn vunuō ne vōwal rak rōw 'ēnē dir ga ul Torres
The locative preposition does not make sense here, and the local adverb 'downwind' occurs on clause level.
All right, then: "We two are going to go to one island which is called Torres. Down there, one island further down(wind) which is called Torres.
ba nik wom 'ēn son naw wom lōl luwo ma si wom van kal gōr gēduō nike kalraka nike 'ir kal den gōr n naw ne le nike
But when you see when the sea is getting big and rising to flood us, get up and stand away to save yourself from the sea to take you.
wo nikm 'ēn n naw dim 'ēqel kel nike sag sur kel
When you see the sea that it lowers again, sit down again."
durum da 'eseneē van van van vavavan
The two did like this on and on.
It got day, and it got night.
ne maran duruk din̄ ēn mē'ērsa
When it got day, the two reached a harbour.
durum kal lēn mē'ērsa lēn vunuō ne vōwal dir ga ul so Hiw lēn Torres 'erē vunuō 'arn̄i vunuō 'a suwēn 'a Torres dir ga ul Hiw
The two came to the shore at a harbour at one island which is called Hiw in the Torres, some islands, a group of islands down at Torres which is called Hiw,
durum van sar lēn mē'ērsa ne vōwal
When the two went into a harbour,
me' ne tek mē die so 'ama' lēn 'an̄sara lēn me' ne tek mē diē so
reef said to him, the ghost in … the person in the reef said to him:
bul duk kal ba'a duk momse ke'i 'ekēgēn du me momse 'alēn 'aklē qōn̄ duk mul kel lēn 'ekē gēdum van ma den
"Friend, we two are going to land and rest for a while here; we will rest here for a few days, and then we go back to where we came from."
The two went inside to the shore at this place,
va n me' m van sar van sar van sar m van sar lēn lēn qil anē'ē m kal ba' 'enteg sar
the reef went inside, went inside, and when it had gone into the bay, had gone well inside,
so no me sag ren̄ kēgēn bak
it said: "I'll be stuck here, but
bul nike row kal sar 'an n 'ekē ga mamasa 'anē'ē
friend, you, jump onto the shore at this dry place here.
nike dar ekēne nike siksik gom ēn gengen rekse sava nik me 'ēn sier m̄as 'alēn nik ga gen nike gen
The possessive classifier for EAT possession plus possessor suffix is incorporated into the VC here and expresses a beneficiary.
and wait there. Search some food for you, like: what you can find in order to eat, eat it.
nike dar gōr si nom tek mē nikē so duk mul kel duk mulō
You wait and if I tell you: "We two are gonna go back home." we'll go home.
nike sōk sier lik ēn 'ōnō mimi'ir nōm nike mi'ir
Further more, find a place to sleep for you and sleep (there).
'alēn masōgi rekse nom ulul kel nikē lēn sav qōn̄ du wom mulō duk mulō
All right, when I am calling you again, on some day that we two are going home, we two go home."
itok duruk van kal di ne van kal row kal sarēn dim 'ōg kelkel 'ōg kelkel n me' ne onon rōw nē'
All right, the two went landwards ... he jumped up onto the shore, and while he was staying there all the time, staying there all the time, the reef was lying down there.
dim 'ōg kelkel van van van vavavavan
He stayed around there on and on,
dim qōn̄ ne vōwal dim mi'ir lik
He ... one night when he slept again,
di ne mi'ir suwō di ne qōrqōr n me' ne van ma ne tēk mē diē so
he slept deep and was dreaming, the reef came and said to him:
gōduō me mul kel qiri lēn kalraka duk 'ēqel
"we two will go back home today at ... get up, let us two go down (off the shore)!
The man got up and followed him,
rekse dim van 'ag ēn qōrqōr ne 'ēqel din̄ rōwē ne vavan kal ma 'an me' n me' mal dar diē rekse ga di mal sal kal
i.e. he went following the dream, went down to the sea, went back onto the reef; the reef had already floated upwards;
n me' mal kalrak den 'onogi a dim on 'i bēne dim sal kal
the reef had already got up from the place where it had been lying, it floated up there (on the surface).
'enei di ga dar diē va'anē so duruk itok rem 'an kolok
Now it was waiting for him: "All right, climb onto my back."
dim rem kal 'an kologim row kal kel 'an me' 'anē so ga itok gēduōm van
He climbed up his back, jumped back up onto the reef: "That's good, we two are going.
nik me da lik rekse gēdum van ma nik da rekse n naw wom van ma ga lōwōo nike 'ir kal n naw wom 'ēqel nike sag sur
Do it again like when we two came here: do it like this: when the sea becomes big, stand up; and when the sea lowers, sit down.
dim row kal rōw 'an kologi duruk 'ēqel va'anē
He jumped (seawards) onto its back, and then the two went down (i.e. moved away from the shore).
durum van van da 'esēne van vavavan 'an kele qōn̄ wunvan qōn̄ vōruō duruk din̄ kel ma n mē'ērsa suw 'a ga lēn man̄ri bēne
They went acting like this until after, I think, two days they reached the harbour again [UNCLEAR]
ban masōgi durum van ma rōwēn me' di ne mōwōrōo ne vōruō bēne
But when they came down, the reef broke into two,
rekse di ne mēlē' kirm̄o' ne vōruō bēne
i.e. it split into two pieces.
ge 'ew'i ga lōwōon kum̄ ga lōwōo ne sag 'i rōwē
The big one, the big reef sat down there,
wo n menre kum̄ 'ane'ē̄ ne van kel sar ne kal 'ō ba'a kel sar ēn 'an̄sara ē lēn lēn mē'ērsa
while this piece of the reef moved towards the shore and took this person up the harbour.
masōgi dim vavavan dim din̄ sar ēn mē'ērsa
When it moved and arrived inside the harbour,
di ne tēk mēn me' ne tēk mēn 'an̄sara ē so nike vidir kal va'anē nike van kal 'enei e raga dirēm da gengen sir nikē 'alēn qōn̄ vēlimē sagē
it said to the reef ... to the man: "Jump upwards now, go upwards. Now everybody up there, they are preparing food for your fifth day.
'enei dirēk ... dirēk lik ēk dirēk ... lēn ma'ava 'anei nik row sur 'a 'enei nik virig kal
Now they ... they take it out ... they ... in the morning you jump down and then run upwards."
'enei dirēm da ba nik 'ovi'i rowrow lukei qiri lēn revrev lēn masōgin laklaka nik mak kalu lēn laklaka
Now they are busy. "But you mustn't come out, yet. Today in the evening, when it's time for the dances, come out to the dances."
itok dim van sar ne vidir sur won wom̄al ne kal lu kel rōw
Ok, he went upwards, jumped down, and the reef moved out (into the sea) again.
masōgi dim van rōw die aqit 'ēn'ēn den ēn vunu luwo Vunu Lava
When it went out, it was far away from Big Island, Vanua Lava,
som da 'i so dim dim sag ren̄ 'ekēnē 'enei dir ga ul ēn wōm̄al 'anē'ē kum̄ō 'anē'ē so din Maltetrag
That made that it got stuck there permanently, and now this reef (w.), (k.) is called 'Maltetrag '.
So, a person is stuck there.
'an̄sara 'anē'ē dim van van kal 'as van sar aq 'i esēnēm (äh) vavan revrev dirēm lik ēn gengen lēn ma'ava dirēm gengen vavanvan rōv'e man revrev dirēk dan laklaka

That other man, he went straight inland, went upwards bending down, then in the afternoon they took the food out (of the stone oven: S.S.) and in the morning they ate until it almost got afternoon and they did the dances.
lēn masōgi dim sagsag 'anē ba di ne susur lik ēn aklē dudu woqe 'enge ne da so reksen nōgin ne sigil di bēne
When he was sitting around, he also sewed some leaves of a tree making up his (clothing S.S.) to decorate himself with (in the appropriate customary way S.S.).
masōgi dirēm dan laklaka lēn rōrōv'en revrev
When they did the dances when it was almost afternoon,
di ne kalu va'anē direm es rak sag ēn laklaka n laklaka rekse wunvan resdōn̄ar [?] n REDUP-dance mu 'ama'
he came out. They started up the dancing, the 'Nangae leaves brooming' dance, a devil dance.
masōgi direm direm qē'ēg 'alēn ga laka
di ne lak lu ma rek va'anē
dim laka rekse dim lak luma lēn 'ow'ow lēn m̄oa laklaka dim lak lu ma
He danced, i.e. he came out dancing before, at the first dance he came out dancing.
m da so vagruō nagi dire 'ēn rak 'ēn diē
The second time they didn't recognize him, yet.
da vag'ōl nagi dire 'ēn rak 'ēn diē
The third they didn't recognize him, yet.
'enei direk dōm so direk gis vagra diē va'anē son sav nē n 'ama' sin 'an̄sara
Now they start to think about holding him tight (to find out, S.S.): what is it then, a ghost or a (living, S.S.) human.
so direm dada 'eno 'alēn ga gis vavarga die lēn vag'ōl nagi a dim lak luma direk gis varga
So they tried to hold him tight, and the third time he danced out, they held him tight.
masōgi direm gis varga die direk sōk sier so 'o din 'an̄sara direm ran̄ den n nogin 'erē wōsisigile
When they held him tight they found out: "Oh, he is a human being." and pulled off his ritual decorations.
They found out: "oh, he is a human being."
'o ba e ge 'anē'ē sa dirs dan gengen sir qiri 'anē
"Oh, but he is the one they prepared the meal for tonight."
itok e direk vesir die di ne kaka mē diren 'erē kaka rekse sivie dim van sivie dim 'ēqel suw lēn Torres
Ok, then they were asking him, and he told them all the stories, like how he went, how he went down to the Torres,
dim es sivie wo sivie dim kel ma m din̄ rekse
how he lived and how he returned hither, and it lasted until … like
dirēm dimdim kel ēn kele qōn̄ vēlimē
they reached another fifth day after that.
so dirēm dan qōn̄ vēlimē mugi
Then they celebrated his fifth day.
dim din̄ kel ma mēn 'eraga sōsōgōgi 'eraga nini'igi lēn vunuō 'a Lēnmerig
He had come back to everybody of his line, his descendents at the village of Lemerig.
I think the story is over here.
